1.body: Ideally we'd not need this library as math primitives are probably best handled in some upstream library. What we need: 18 decimal fixed point math handle rounding directions explicitly rescale non-18 decimal fixed point values (e.g. ERC20 token amounts) to/from 18 decimals so that we can do math on them avoid code bloat in an interpreter due to importing several libs with heavily overlapping scope open source license, but not forcing ppl to jump on the GPL crusade minimal surface area so we can gracefully deprecate this lib if all the above is provided elsewhere someday works on simple uint256 values Upstream candidates: Open Zeppelin Has implementations that include rounding direction 👍 Audited code due to recent ERC4626 implementation 👍 Only includes math needed by the specs implemented, not general purpose 👎 PRB math General purpose fixed point math 👍 Where the scope overlaps OZ the logic is similar or identical 👍 No ability to specify rounding or to rescale outside 18 decimals 👎 Never audited 👎 Others Either wrong license or issues as pointed out on PRB math repo Since we need math that isn't provided by Open Zeppelin, and we aren't going to write it ourselves, PRB math seems to be the most reasonable foundation. At the same time, Open Zeppelin may already be a dependency for other reasons, such as some token implementation, so including both OZ and PRB in a single contract can bloat code.
1.title: Goals

10.body: Value of "one" for fixed point math. uint256 constant FIXED_POINT_ONE = 1e18;
10.title: FIXED_POINT_ONE

11.body: Calculations MUST round up. uint256 constant FLAG_ROUND_UP = 1;
11.title: FLAG_ROUND_UP

12.body: Calculations MUST saturate NOT overflow. uint256 constant FLAG_SATURATE = 1 << 1;
12.title: FLAG_SATURATE

13.body: Flags MUST NOT exceed this value. uint256 constant FLAG_MAX_INT = FLAG_SATURATE | FLAG_ROUND_UP;
13.title: FLAG_MAX_INT

14.body: Can't represent this many OOMs of decimals in uint256. uint256 constant OVERFLOW_RESCALE_OOMS = 78;
14.title: OVERFLOW_RESCALE_OOMS

15.body: Git Source Tools to scale unsigned values to/from 18 decimal fixed point representation. Overflows error and underflows are rounded up or down explicitly. The max uint256 as decimal is roughly 1e77 so scaling values comparable to 1e18 is unlikely to ever overflow in most contexts. For a typical use case involving tokens, the entire supply of a token rescaled up a full 18 decimals would still put it "only" in the region of ~1e40 which has a full 30 orders of magnitude buffer before running into saturation issues. However, there's no theoretical reason that a token or any other use case couldn't use large numbers or extremely precise decimals that would push this library to overflow point, so it MUST be treated with caution around the edge cases. Scaling down ANY fixed point decimal also reduces the precision which can lead to dust or in the worst case trapped funds if subsequent subtraction overflows a rounded-down number. Consider using saturating subtraction for safety against previously downscaled values, and whether trapped dust is a significant issue. If you need to retain full/arbitrary precision in the case of downscaling DO NOT use this library. All rescaling and/or division operations in this library require a rounding flag. This allows and forces the caller to specify where dust sits due to rounding. For example the caller could round up when taking tokens from msg.sender and round down when returning them, ensuring that any dust in the round trip accumulates in the contract rather than opening an exploit or reverting and trapping all funds. This is exactly how the ERC4626 vault spec handles dust and is a good reference point in general. Typically the contract holding tokens and non-interactive participants should be favoured by rounding calculations rather than active participants. This is because we assume that an active participant, e.g. msg.sender, knowns something we don't and is carefully crafting an attack, so we are most conservative and suspicious of their inputs and actions.
15.title: FixedPointDecimalScale

17.body: Scales a_ up by a specified number of decimals. function scaleUp(uint256 a_, uint256 scaleUpBy_) internal pure returns (uint256 b_); Parameters Name Type Description a_ uint256 The number to scale up. scaleUpBy_ uint256 Number of orders of magnitude to scale b_ up by. Errors if overflows. Returns Name Type Description b_ uint256 a_ scaled up by scaleUpBy_.
17.title: scaleUp

18.body: Identical to scaleUp but saturates instead of reverting on overflow. function scaleUpSaturating(uint256 a_, uint256 scaleUpBy_) internal pure returns (uint256 c_); Parameters Name Type Description a_ uint256 As per scaleUp. scaleUpBy_ uint256 As per scaleUp. Returns Name Type Description c_ uint256 As per scaleUp but saturates as type(uint256).max on overflow.
18.title: scaleUpSaturating

19.body: Scales a_ down by a specified number of decimals, rounding in the specified direction. Used internally by several other functions in this lib. function scaleDown(uint256 a_, uint256 scaleDownBy_) internal pure returns (uint256); Parameters Name Type Description a_ uint256 The number to scale down. scaleDownBy_ uint256 Number of orders of magnitude to scale a_ down by. Overflows if greater than 77. Returns Name Type Description <none> uint256 c_ a_ scaled down by scaleDownBy_ and rounded.
19.title: scaleDown

20.body: function scaleDownRoundUp(uint256 a_, uint256 scaleDownBy_) internal pure returns (uint256 c_);
20.title: scaleDownRoundUp

21.body: Scale a fixed point decimal of some scale factor to 18 decimals. function scale18(uint256 a_, uint256 decimals_, uint256 flags_) internal pure returns (uint256); Parameters Name Type Description a_ uint256 Some fixed point decimal value. decimals_ uint256 The number of fixed decimals of a_. flags_ uint256 Controls rounding and saturation. Returns Name Type Description <none> uint256 a_ scaled to 18 decimals.
21.title: scale18

22.body: Scale an 18 decimal fixed point value to some other scale. Exactly the inverse behaviour of scale18. Where scale18 would scale up, scaleN scales down, and vice versa. function scaleN(uint256 a_, uint256 targetDecimals_, uint256 flags_) internal pure returns (uint256); Parameters Name Type Description a_ uint256 An 18 decimal fixed point number. targetDecimals_ uint256 The new scale of a_. flags_ uint256 Controls rounding and saturation. Returns Name Type Description <none> uint256 a_ rescaled from 18 to targetDecimals_.
22.title: scaleN

23.body: Scale a fixed point up or down by scaleBy_ orders of magnitude. Notably scaleBy is a SIGNED integer so scaling down by negative OOMS is supported. function scaleBy(uint256 a_, int8 scaleBy_, uint256 flags_) internal pure returns (uint256); Parameters Name Type Description a_ uint256 Some integer of any scale. scaleBy_ int8 OOMs to scale a_ up or down by. This is a SIGNED int8 which means it can be negative, and also means that sign extension MUST be considered if changing it to another type. flags_ uint256 Controls rounding and saturating. Returns Name Type Description <none> uint256 a_ rescaled according to scaleBy_.
23.title: scaleBy

24.body: Scale an 18 decimal fixed point ratio of a_:b_ according to the decimals of a and b that each MAY NOT be 18. i.e. a subsequent call to a_.fixedPointMul(ratio_) would yield the value that it would have as though a_ and b_ were both 18 decimals and we hadn't rescaled the ratio. This is similar to scaleBy that calcualates the OOMs to scale by as bDecimals_ - aDecimals_. function scaleRatio(uint256 ratio_, uint8 aDecimals_, uint8 bDecimals_, uint256 flags_) internal pure returns (uint256); Parameters Name Type Description ratio_ uint256 The ratio to be scaled. aDecimals_ uint8 The decimals of the ratio numerator. bDecimals_ uint8 The decimals of the ratio denominator. flags_ uint256 Controls rounding and saturating.
24.title: scaleRatio

3.body: Provide a base repo (this one) that has zero dependencies, to focus on the logic required to rescale between decimals, that are lib agnostic. Provide supporting repos to normalise Open Zeppelin and PRB math OZ includes muldiv but doesn't have an opinion on decimals, so caller is forced to provide "one" at every step and mentally balance multiplication and division PRB is opinionated with sane defaults for 18 decimal math but provides no rounding or rescaling support Downstream consumers are advised to select one of either OZ or PRB to compile into their contracts, using the relevant supporting libs only, to minimise dependencies and potential code bloat, or even inconsistent behaviours between libs.
3.title: Approach

6.body: Fixed point multiplication in 18 decimal fixed point. Both a and b MUST be 18 decimal fixed point values. Implemented in terms of Open Zeppelin Math library. function fixedPointMul(uint256 a, uint256 b, Math.Rounding rounding) internal pure returns (uint256); Parameters Name Type Description a uint256 First term. b uint256 Second term. rounding Math.Rounding Rounding direction as per Open Zeppelin Math. Returns Name Type Description <none> uint256 a multiplied by b in 18 fixed point decimals.
6.title: fixedPointMul

7.body: Fixed point division in 18 decimal fixed point. Both a and b MUST be 18 decimal fixed point values. Implemented in terms of Open Zeppelin Math library. function fixedPointDiv(uint256 a, uint256 b, Math.Rounding rounding) internal pure returns (uint256); Parameters Name Type Description a uint256 First term. b uint256 Second term. rounding Math.Rounding Rounding direction as per Open Zeppelin Math. Returns Name Type Description <none> uint256 a divided by b in 18 fixed point decimals.
7.title: fixedPointDiv

9.body: The scale of all fixed point math. This is adopting the conventions of both ETH (wei) and most ERC20 tokens, so is hopefully uncontroversial. uint256 constant FIXED_POINT_DECIMALS = 18;
9.title: FIXED_POINT_DECIMALS
